# No Docstrings or Inline Comments

Never add docstrings to functions. Never add comments above or beside lines of code.

A function's name, arguments, and body should speak for themselves. Comments duplicate meaning, create a maintenance burden when the code changes, and can actively mislead when they fall out of sync.

```python
# BAD
def lookup(dependency_name: str) -> dict | None:
    """Look up a dependency in the component database."""
    # Normalise the name before comparing
    needle = _normalise(dependency_name)
    # Iterate over all components
    for component in db["components"]:
        ...

# GOOD
def lookup(dependency_name: str) -> dict | None:
    needle = _normalise(dependency_name)
    for component in db["components"]:
        ...
```

Only add a comment when there is no other way to convey the information — for example, a non-obvious workaround for an external system's bug, or a legal/licence notice.
